    interviewQuestion: "Your user table has 500M rows and a single DB can't handle the write load. How do you shard it?",
    modelAnswer: "Hash shard by user_id — user_id % N_shards routes to correct shard. Ensures even distribution regardless of signup date. 16 shards with ability to split to 32, 64 later using consistent hashing. Each shard has its own primary + replica. Application-level shard router (or middleware like Vitess) hides sharding from application code. For cross-shard operations like 'find all users in a city', maintain a separate search index (Elasticsearch) that's not sharded by user_id.",
