  "mock-walkthrough": {
    id: "mock-walkthrough",
    intuition: "Reading about system design and doing system design interviews are completely different skills. Mock practice is the single highest-ROI activity for interview prep. Here's a complete walkthrough template to practice with.",
    technicalDetail: "Template for any system design problem: Opening (30s): 'Before I start designing, let me clarify a few requirements.' Requirements (5 min): Functional: 3-4 core features. Non-functional: scale, latency, availability. 'I'll assume X to keep scope manageable.' Estimation (5 min): DAU → QPS. Storage per unit → total storage. 'At 10M DAU with 100 posts/day average = 1B posts/day...' API (3 min): List 3-5 endpoints. 'POST /posts, GET /feed?cursor=X, GET /posts/:id.' HLD (10 min): Draw boxes. Narrate each: 'Client hits CDN for static assets, CDN misses go to LB, LB routes to stateless app servers, which read from Redis cache first, DB on miss.' Deep Dive #1 (10 min): State problem → naive solution → improved solution → failure modes. Deep Dive #2 (8 min): Same structure. Failure Modes (3 min): 'If Redis goes down, traffic falls through to DB — add circuit breaker. If DB primary fails, replica promotes in 30s — add automated failover with monitoring.' Wrap-up (1 min): 'Summary: I designed X using Y approach. Main tradeoffs: A vs B. Would monitor Z.'",
    tradeoffs: ["Rushing to HLD: misses requirements that change the design", "Too much time on easy parts: no time left for the hard parts that impress interviewers"],
    realWorldExample: "Interviewing.io data: candidates who do 5+ mock interviews before real interviews have a 2.5x higher pass rate than those who do 0-1 mocks. The practice of thinking out loud is a separate skill from the design knowledge.",
    interviewQuestion: "Walk me through how you'd design a notification system.",
    modelAnswer: "Requirements: push/email/SMS, 1B users, 10M notifications/day. QPS: ~115/sec. Architecture: NotificationService → type router → Push (FCM/APNS), Email (SES/SendGrid), SMS (Twilio) → each via dedicated queue. Deep dive: fan-out at scale (user has 1000 followers, one event → 1000 notifications → process async via Kafka). Failure: SMS provider down → retry with exponential backoff, dead-letter queue for manual review. Monitoring: delivery rate per channel, p99 delivery latency.",
    commonMistakes: ["Practicing by reading solutions instead of designing from scratch", "Practicing alone — needs to be out loud, ideally with a mock interviewer"],
    memoryTrick: "REACH: Requirements → Estimation → API → Components (HLD) → Hard parts (deep dives).",
    relatedConcepts: ["45-minute-clock", "communication-patterns", "top-50-questions", "deep-dives"],
    cheatSheetLine: "Template: 5min reqs → 5min estimate → 3min API → 10min HLD → 10min deep dive → 3min failure → 1min summary. REACH framework. Practice out loud.",
  },

  "question-types": {
    id: "question-types",
    intuition: "Every system design question falls into one of ~8 categories. Recognizing the category instantly tells you the key design patterns to apply — just like recognizing a DP problem tells you to look for optimal substructure.",
    technicalDetail: "Storage: URL shortener, Pastebin, KV store, File sync (Dropbox). Key patterns: content-addressable storage (hash → ID), deduplication, chunking, consistent hashing for distribution. Social Feed: Twitter, Facebook, Instagram, Reddit. Key patterns: fan-out on write vs read, celebrity problem, feed ranking, infinite scroll with cursor pagination. Real-time Messaging: WhatsApp, Discord, Slack. Key patterns: WebSocket connection management, message ordering, offline delivery, end-to-end encryption. Video Streaming: YouTube, Netflix, Twitch. Key patterns: chunked upload, transcoding pipeline, adaptive bitrate, CDN placement. Location/Matching: Uber, Doordash, Airbnb. Key patterns: geospatial indexing (Geohash, S2, R-tree), real-time matching, ETA calculation. Search/ML: Typeahead, Google Search, Spotify Recommendations. Key patterns: inverted index, trie, collaborative filtering, feature store. Infrastructure: Rate limiter, notification system, job scheduler, logging pipeline. Key patterns: distributed counters, fan-out, cron semantics, structured logging + time series DB. Transaction: Payment gateway, booking, inventory. Key patterns: idempotency, saga/2PC, exactly-once semantics, optimistic locking.",
    tradeoffs: ["Recognizing type too quickly: you may apply the wrong pattern if problem has unusual constraints", "Over-fitting to type: each problem has unique requirements — use type as starting point, not final answer"],
    realWorldExample: "When Airbnb interviewer says 'design a search experience,' the question type is Location/Search hybrid. Pattern: geospatial index for proximity + inverted index for text matching + ML ranking. Knowing both patterns means you can cover both dimensions confidently.",
    interviewQuestion: "How do you approach a system design question you've never seen before?",
    modelAnswer: "Identify the type: is this storage, social, messaging, streaming, location, search, infra, or transaction? That gives you the starting patterns. Then ask clarifying questions to understand the unique constraints. Apply the known pattern and adapt. Example: 'Design a food delivery tracking system' = location type (real-time tracking) + messaging type (order status updates). Apply geospatial + WebSocket patterns.",
    commonMistakes: ["Not categorizing the problem — treating every question as unique makes it harder to apply known patterns", "Applying a pattern without checking it fits the specific requirements"],
    memoryTrick: "8 types: Storage → Social → Messaging → Streaming → Location → Search/ML → Infrastructure → Transaction. Map question to type, apply type pattern.",
    relatedConcepts: ["top-50-questions", "high-level-architecture", "45-minute-clock", "deep-dives"],
    cheatSheetLine: "8 types: Storage/Social/Messaging/Streaming/Location/Search/Infra/Transaction. Each has signature patterns. Identify type → apply pattern → adapt to constraints.",
  },

