  "8-scaling-moves": {
    id: "8-scaling-moves",
    intuition: "Every scaling problem in distributed systems reduces to one of 8 fundamental moves. When an interviewer presents a bottleneck, you should be able to recognize which move solves it — like recognizing an algorithm pattern in coding problems.",
    technicalDetail: "Move 1 — Cache: store computed results close to the requester. Removes load from DB or expensive computations. Redis, CDN, in-process cache. When: read-heavy, data has temporal locality. Move 2 — Replicate: copy data to multiple nodes for read scale and fault tolerance. Read replicas, CDN edge nodes, caching tiers. When: reads >> writes, geographic distribution needed. Move 3 — Shard / Partition: split data across multiple nodes for write scale. Horizontal sharding by user_id, hash, or range. When: write volume exceeds single node capacity. Move 4 — Async: put work in a queue, process it in the background. Kafka, SQS, RabbitMQ. When: operation can tolerate eventual processing (email, notifications, analytics). Move 5 — Precompute (Materialize): compute results ahead of time and store them. Fan-out on write (pre-compute user feeds), aggregation tables, materialized views. When: read pattern is predictable, write is infrequent relative to reads. Move 6 — Approximate: sacrifice perfect accuracy for orders-of-magnitude scale improvement. HyperLogLog for unique count (instead of exact set), Count-Min Sketch for frequency, Bloom filter for set membership. When: exact result not required (trending topics, unique visitor count). Move 7 — Compress: reduce data volume. Columnar storage, run-length encoding, gzip. When: network or storage is the bottleneck. Move 8 — Offload: move work to specialized systems closer to the data or user. CDN for static assets, edge computing for personalization, FPGA for cryptography. When: general-purpose systems are doing work that specialized systems do 10x better.",
    tradeoffs: ["Each move adds complexity; combine only when necessary", "Precompute trades write overhead for read speed — only worthwhile if reads >> writes"],
    realWorldExample: "Twitter's 'Fail Whale' was a sharding problem. Fix = Shard. Redis was the cache fix (replaces DB reads). Kafka for async fan-out (Async). CDN for media (Offload). HyperLogLog for tweet impression counts (Approximate). Feed precompute via timeline service (Precompute). All 8 moves used in one system.",
    interviewQuestion: "Your API response time is 500ms. How do you get it to 50ms?",
    modelAnswer: "Trace the request: is DB the bottleneck? Apply Cache (Redis L1). Is it fan-out? Apply Async (queue). Is it data volume? Apply Compress (gzip response, columnar). Is it geographic distance? Apply Offload (CDN). Is it heavy computation? Apply Precompute (nightly job). Identify the actual bottleneck first, then apply the right move.",
    commonMistakes: ["Applying 3 moves when 1 is sufficient — complexity for its own sake", "Caching before profiling — you might cache the wrong thing"],
    memoryTrick: "CRSA-PAO: Cache, Replicate, Shard, Async, Precompute, Approximate, (O)ffload, (Compress).",
    relatedConcepts: ["caching", "sharding", "replication", "message-queues"],
    cheatSheetLine: "8 moves: Cache, Replicate, Shard, Async, Precompute, Approximate, Compress, Offload. Match move to bottleneck type. Don't combine unless needed.",
  },

  "what-breaks-first": {
    id: "what-breaks-first",
    intuition: "'What breaks first' is the heuristic for systematic bottleneck analysis. Before designing a scaling solution, trace the request path and identify the first component that fails under target load. This prevents over-engineering and focuses effort on the actual constraint.",
    technicalDetail: "Request path analysis: Client → DNS → CDN → LB → App Server → Cache → DB. At each hop: what's the capacity? what happens when it's exceeded? DNS: typically not a bottleneck (Anycast + TTL caching). Handles millions of QPS. CDN: rarely a bottleneck. Handles petabytes. LB: L4 can handle millions of connections, L7 ~100K concurrent. Not usually the bottleneck. App Server: stateless, horizontally scalable. Typical: 100-1000 RPS per instance depending on complexity. Bottleneck when: CPU-heavy computation, or too many DB calls per request. Cache (Redis): 100K+ ops/sec per node. Can bottleneck with hot keys. DB: the most common first bottleneck. Postgres single-node: ~1K writes/sec (IOPS-limited), ~10K reads/sec. Bottleneck appears as: high p99 latency, connection pool exhaustion, disk I/O at 100%. Capacity math: current QPS × growth multiplier = future QPS. Compare to known capacity limits. Find the first component where future QPS > capacity. That's what breaks first. Common first bottlenecks in order: DB write throughput, DB connection pool, DB read IOPS, cache hot keys, app server CPU (heavy computation), network bandwidth (large file transfers).",
    tradeoffs: ["Optimizing the wrong layer: CPU optimization when DB is the bottleneck wastes time", "Pre-optimizing: adding sharding before hitting limits adds unnecessary complexity"],
    realWorldExample: "Facebook's early architecture (PHP + MySQL): at 10M users, the MySQL DB was the first bottleneck (IOPS limited). Fix: Memcache layer. At 100M: Memcache hot keys. Fix: regional Memcache pools. At 500M: MySQL write throughput. Fix: sharding. Each stage fixed the specific constraint, not the next one.",
    interviewQuestion: "How do you decide what to optimize first in a slow system?",
    modelAnswer: "Add distributed tracing (Jaeger) and profiling. Find the p99 latency breakdown: where does each request spend its time? DB queries typically account for 60-80% of API latency. Profile DB: slow query log, EXPLAIN ANALYZE. Fix the highest-impact query first: add index, optimize N+1, add cache. Measure again. Repeat. Never optimize without measuring first.",
    commonMistakes: ["Over-architecting: designing for 100x scale when 10x is the actual requirement", "Guessing the bottleneck without measuring: the bottleneck is almost never where you think"],
    memoryTrick: "Trace the request. Time each hop. The slowest hop = what breaks first. Fix it. Repeat.",
    relatedConcepts: ["8-scaling-moves", "observability", "back-of-envelope", "database-indexing"],
    cheatSheetLine: "Trace request path → time each hop → DB is usually first bottleneck → add cache → add replica → shard if needed. Measure before optimizing.",
  },

